<paragraph blockId="13.[213,1169,1357,1573]" pageId="13" pageNumber="2935">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Shih, Ko and Polaszek" authorityYear="2008" box="[213,437,1358,1382]" class="Insecta" family="Aphelinidae" genus="Encarsia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="2935" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="magnalata">
<emphasis box="[213,437,1358,1382]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="2935">Encarsia magnalata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is close to 
<taxonomicName authority="(Silvestri)" baseAuthorityName="Silvestri" baseAuthorityYear="1926" box="[580,785,1357,1382]" class="Insecta" family="Aphelinidae" genus="Encarsia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="2935" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ishii">
<emphasis box="[580,662,1358,1382]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="2935">E. ishii</emphasis>
(Silvestri)
</taxonomicName>
, to which it keys in 
<bibRefCitation author="Huang J &amp; Polaszek A" pageId="13" pageNumber="2935" pagination="1825 - 1966" refId="ref8787" refString="Huang J, Polaszek A. 1998. A revision of the Chinese species of Encarsia Forster (Hymenoptera: Aphelindae): Parasitoids of whiteflies, scale insects and Aphids (Homoptera: Aleyrodidae, Diaspididae, Aphidoidea). J Nat Hist. 32: 1825 - 1966." type="journal article" year="1998">Huang and Polaszek (1998)</bibRefCitation>
. It differs from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Silvestri" baseAuthorityYear="1926" box="[580,659,1389,1413]" class="Insecta" family="Aphelinidae" genus="Encarsia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="2935" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ishii">
<emphasis box="[580,659,1389,1413]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="2935">E. ishii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having the fore wing hyaline, fewer setae on the lateral gastral terga and, probably most importantly, a longer and narrower F1. Morphology of the male when found, coupled with molecular studies, will determine whether the above-mentioned morphological differences – normally reliable indicators of species differences in this genus – represent good species indicators or simply intraspecific variation.
</paragraph>
